: In {{ill|1789|ja|1789年}} ({{ill|Kansei 1|ja|寛政元年}}), following the {{ill|Kunashir-Menashi Rebellion|ja|クナシリ・メナシの戦い}}, the Matsumae Domain removed Hidaya Kyūbē from his trade rights in Eastern Ezo and assigned Denbē to oversee relief efforts for the Ainu.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=81}}

: In {{ill|1790|ja|1790年}} ({{ill|Kansei 2|ja|寛政2nd year }}), he launched an expedition to develop a trading site in {{ill|Sakhalin|ja|樺太}}, and by {{ill|1798|ja|1798年}} ({{ill|Kansei 10|ja|寛政10年}}), he was hailed as the "Eastern Yokozuna" alongside {{ill|Kōnoike Zen'emon|ja|鴻池善右衛門}} in the national wealth rankings.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=82}}

: However, in {{ill|1796|ja|1796年}} ({{ill|Kansei 8|ja|寛政8年}}), he was abruptly removed from his trade rights due to political maneuvering by Osaka merchant Koyama Gonbē.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=83}} His fortunes were later restored, and in {{ill|1799|ja|1799年}} ({{ill|Kansei 11|ja|寛政11th year }}), the Tokugawa Shogunate made him an official government trade manager in Ezo.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=84}}

: In {{ill|1915|ja|1915th year }} ({{ill|Taishō 4|ja|大正4th year }}), he was posthumously awarded the {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank|ja|従五位|1=Junior Fifth Rank}}.{{Sfn|Tajiri|1975|p=39}}

