[[Matsumae Domain]] trader and agent {{ill|Murayama Denbee|ja|村山伝兵衛|qq=draft}} (1738–1813) is said to have founded the small shrine of {{nihongo|Sōya Daijingū|宗谷大神宮}} In [[Tenmei]] 5 (1785), enshrining [[Amaterasu]] as guardian of the north gate.<ref name="Jinjacho">{{cite web |url=https://hokkaidojinjacho.jp/北門神社/ |script-title=ja:北門神社 |trans-title=Hokumon Jinja |language=Japanese |publisher=Hokkaidō Jinja-chō |accessdate=28 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.city.wakkanai.hokkaido.jp/gaiyo/ayumi.html |script-title=ja:稚内のあゆみ（歴史）|trans-title=History of Wakkanai |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Wakkanai, Hokkaido|Wakkanai City]] |accessdate=28 September 2019}}</ref> In 1896 the shrine was transferred to its current location and renamed [[Hokumon Shrine]], with [[Takemikazuchi]] and [[Kotoshironushi]] enshrined alongside Amaterasu.<ref name="Jinjacho"/>

==Overview==
'''Murayama Denbē''' (村山 伝兵衛) was a merchant who expanded from {{ill|Noto Province|ja|能登国|qq=draft}} to {{ill|Ezo|ja|蝦夷地|qq=draft}} during the {{ill|Genroku era|ja|元禄|qq=draft}}. The name "Denbē" was passed down through successive heads of the Murayama family.

The Murayama family's business was known as '''Abe-ya''' (安部屋 or 阿部屋), and their shop emblem was '''Marujūgo''' (○に十五), symbolizing the first Denbē's ambition to own 15 ships.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=79}}

== Successive Heads of the Murayama Family ==

; First Generation: Murayama Denbē
: {{ill|October 5, 1683|ja|1683rd year 10月5日|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Tenna 3|ja|天和3rd year|qq=draft}}{{ill|8th month, 15th day (lunar calendar)|ja|8月15日 (旧暦)|qq=draft}}) – {{ill|June 4, 1757|ja|1757th year 6月4日|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Hōreki 7|ja|宝暦7th year|qq=draft}}{{ill|4th month, 18th day (lunar calendar)|ja|4月18日 (旧暦)|qq=draft}})
: Born in {{ill|Hakui District|ja|羽咋郡|qq=draft}}, Noto Province, he moved to {{ill|Matsumae Domain|ja|松前藩|qq=draft}} in his late teens or early twenties. He initially stayed at the home of a Matsumae retainer, Kudō Hachirōemon, while starting his business.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=79}} Some records indicate he may have worked as a servant for Harue Jinbē, who had already established Abe-ya in Matsumae.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=79}}
: To gain residency in Matsumae, he became the adopted son of Furuya Kanzayemon, a ship captain serving the Matsumae Domain. He then established a shop in the castle town. Though he never reached 15 ships, he owned five, and he was entrusted with managing trade sites in {{ill|Sōya District, Hokkaido|ja|宗谷郡|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Tomamae District, Hokkaido|ja|苫前郡|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Rumoi District, Hokkaido|ja|留萌郡|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Ishikari District, Hokkaido|ja|石狩郡|qq=draft}} under the domain's direct control. He is also credited with teaching fishing techniques to the {{ill|Ainu|ja|アイヌ|qq=draft}}.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=79}}

; Second Generation: Murayama Rihei
: {{ill|1716|ja|1716th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Kyōhō 1|ja|享保元年|qq=draft}}) – {{ill|1770|ja|1770th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Meiwa 7|ja|明和7th year|qq=draft}})
: The son of Shimazaki Hanbē from {{ill|Tsuruga Port|ja|敦賀港|qq=draft}}. He worked for the Matsumae branch of the Omi merchant Manya Kiemon before being adopted as Denbē's son-in-law.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=79}}
: Though he had two children, he later left the Murayama family for unknown reasons and died at the home of Yamaguchi-ya Ihei in {{ill|Osaka|ja|大阪|qq=draft}}.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=80}}

; Third Generation: Murayama Denbē (Hyōemon)
: {{ill|1738|ja|1738th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Genbun 3|ja|元文3rd year|qq=draft}}) – {{ill|February 8, 1813|ja|1813rd year 2月8日|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Bunka 10|ja|文化10th year|qq=draft}}{{ill|1st month, 8th day (lunar calendar)|ja|1月8日 (旧暦)|qq=draft}})
: After his grandfather's death, he inherited the family business. During the {{ill|Meiwa era|ja|明和|qq=draft}}, he took over part of the Ishikari trade site. By {{ill|1775|ja|1775th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|An'ei 4|ja|安永4th year|qq=draft}}), he controlled the Sōya trade site, and in {{ill|1778|ja|1778th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|An'ei 7|ja|安永7th year|qq=draft}}), he acquired the {{ill|Mashike District, Hokkaido|ja|増毛郡|qq=draft}} trade site.
: His success led to permission for {{ill|samurai|ja|苗字帯刀|qq=draft}}, and he also served as {{ill|Machi toshiyori|ja|町年寄|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Machi bugyō|ja|町奉行|qq=draft}} assistant, becoming a key figure in the region.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=80}}

: In {{ill|1789|ja|1789th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Kansei 1|ja|寛政元年|qq=draft}}), following the {{ill|Kunashir-Menashi Rebellion|ja|クナシリ・メナシの戦い|qq=draft}}, the Matsumae Domain removed Hidaya Kyūbē from his trade rights in Eastern Ezo and assigned Denbē to oversee relief efforts for the Ainu.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=81}}

: In {{ill|1790|ja|1790th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Kansei 2|ja|寛政2nd year|qq=draft}}), he launched an expedition to develop a trading site in {{ill|Sakhalin|ja|樺太|qq=draft}}, and by {{ill|1798|ja|1798th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Kansei 10|ja|寛政10th year|qq=draft}}), he was hailed as the "Eastern Yokozuna" alongside {{ill|Kōnoike Zen'emon|ja|鴻池善右衛門|qq=draft}} in the national wealth Rankings.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=82}}

: However, in {{ill|1796|ja|1796th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Kansei 8|ja|寛政8th year|qq=draft}}), he was abruptly removed from his trade rights due to political maneuvering by Osaka merchant Koyama Gonbē.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=83}} His fortunes were later restored, and in {{ill|1799|ja|1799th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Kansei 11|ja|寛政11th year|qq=draft}}), the Tokugawa Shogunate made him an official government trade manager in Ezo.{{Sfn|Itō|2008|p=84}}

: In {{ill|1915|ja|1915th year|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Taishō 4|ja|大正4th year|qq=draft}}), he was posthumously awarded the {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank|ja|従五位|1=Junior Fifth Rank|qq=draft}}.{{Sfn|Tajiri|1975|p=39}}

